\begin_layout Section
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Einstein's general theory of relativity uses the notion of geodesic – the
 shortest length path between two points – in its description.
 It reduces to the special theory of relativity in the special case of flat
 space(time).
 In addition to studying geodesics we will generalise the notion of parallel
 vectors to the non-Eucledian case.
 We will connect this to a scheme for detecting the curvature of the underlying
 space.
 (I myself don't know where this would be used in GR but we will see.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Geodesic Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first find a suitable way of representing a curve in an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 dimensional space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We could define 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 coordinates in terms of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{\text{th}}$
\end_inset

 coordinate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is how we usually describe a line for instance.
 The difficulty with this method is that it doesn't preserve the symmetry
 of the coordinates – one of the coordinates is given a special treatment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(2)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 equations in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is symmetric in its treatment of the coordinates but it is implicit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(3)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Parametric description: Define the curve in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{i}=f^{i}(u)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is a parameter which changes monotonically as you move along the curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is both explicit and preserves the symmetry.
 We will use this scheme for describing our curves.
 The drawback of this scheme is that different parametrizations may describe
 different curves but we will handle this appropriately when needed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the variational approach to derive the differential equation for
 a geodesic.
 Consider a curve described by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{i}=f^{i}(u)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u=0$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the starting point and 
\begin_inset Formula $u=1$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the ending point.
 Let us pretend that this curve already represents the shortest path between
 the two extreme points.
 Now consider some arbitrary nearby curve starting and ending at the same
 point as given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{i}=f^{i}(u)+\delta f^{i}(u)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta f^{i}(0)=0=\delta f^{i}(1)$
\end_inset

.
 We can evaluate the length of a given curve as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\int_{\text{curve}}ds=\int_{\text{curve}}du.\frac{ds}{du}=\int_{0}^{1}du\left.\sqrt{g_{ij}\frac{dx^{i}}{du}\frac{dx^{j}}{du}}\right|_{x^{i}=f^{i}(u)}.
\]

\end_inset

Now the change in length between this curve and the arbitrary nearby curve
 must vanish to first order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x^{k}$
\end_inset

 as we assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{i}$
\end_inset

 already represents the geodesic where the small parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x^{k}:=f^{i}-\left(f^{i}-\delta f^{i}\right)=\delta f^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This difference will be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta L=\int_{0}^{1}du\frac{1}{2}\left(g_{mn}\frac{dx^{m}}{du}\frac{dx^{n}}{du}\right)^{-1/2}\left\{ \partial_{k}g_{ij}\delta x^{k}\frac{dx^{i}}{du}\frac{dx^{j}}{du}+2g_{ij}\frac{d(\delta x^{i})}{du}\frac{dx^{j}}{du}+\cancel{g_{ij}\frac{dx^{i}}{du}\frac{d(\delta x^{j})}{du}}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

where the last two terms are the same which explains the factor of two.
 The goal here is to obtain an expression of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}du(\dots)\delta x^{k}+(\dots)\mathcal{O}(\delta x^{2})\dots$
\end_inset

 so that we can demand the first bracket to be zero to obtain a differential
 equation for the geodesic
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Atul: admittedly we only extremised the length and therefore it might even
 be the longest length curve but since that in most cases the longest curve
 would have infinite length I think the result here would apply to shortest
 length curves as we start with assuming a finite length curve.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 At this point it helps to use what is known as an 
\emph on
affine parameter
\emph default
 – the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is such that equal 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 spans equal distance along the curve.
 Thus an affine parameter must satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{du}\left[\left(g_{ij}\frac{dx^{i}}{du}\frac{dx^{j}}{du}\right)^{1/2}\right]=0.
\]

\end_inset

We will now perform an integration by parts of the second term in the sum
 (in the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L$
\end_inset

) to get 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}du\left(\dots\right)\delta x^{i}\left[\frac{d}{du}\left(2g_{ij}\frac{dx^{j}}{du}\right)\right]+\cancel{\left[\left(\dots\right)\delta x^{i}\left(\dots\right)\right]_{u=0}^{u=1}}$
\end_inset

 which yields
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
note the affine parameter assumption allows us to neglect the effect of
 the coefficient multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $du$
\end_inset

 which lets us cancel the surface term
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta L=\int_{0}^{1}du\frac{1}{2}\left(g_{mn}\frac{dx^{m}}{du}\frac{dx^{n}}{du}\right)^{-1/2}\delta x^{k}\underbrace{\left\{ \partial_{k}g_{ij}\frac{dx^{i}}{du}\frac{dx^{j}}{du}-2\frac{dg_{kj}}{du}\frac{dx^{j}}{du}-2g_{kj}\frac{d^{2}x^{j}}{du^{2}}\right\} }_{\text{must vanish}}.
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L$
\end_inset

 to be zero to first order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x^{k}$
\end_inset

, manifestly then, the term indicated must vanish.
 Multiplying this term by 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{1}{2}g^{lk}$
\end_inset

, using the chain rule for the derivative of the metric and equating it
 to zero one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}x^{l}}{du^{2}}+g^{lk}\frac{dx^{j}}{du}\partial_{m}g_{kj}\frac{dx^{m}}{du}-\frac{1}{2}g^{lk}g_{ij}\frac{dx^{i}}{du}\frac{dx^{j}}{du}=0.
\]

\end_inset

From the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{l}{}_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and the symmetry in 
\begin_inset Formula $ij$
\end_inset

 one obtains (small exercise) the final form of the 
\emph on
geodesic equation
\emph default
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\frac{d^{2}x^{l}}{du^{2}}+\Gamma^{l}{}_{ij}\frac{dx^{i}}{du}\frac{dx^{j}}{du}=0.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some consistency checks: Note that (exercise) 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{du}\left(g_{mn}\frac{dx^{m}}{du}\frac{dx^{n}}{du}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 follows from the geodesic equation.
 Note also (again left as an exercise) that changing the coordinate system
 leaves the form of the geodesic equation unchanged.
 This is expected as we did not make any assumptions about the coordinate
 system in the derivation but we did assume the parameter to be affine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us find the geodesic for flat space.
 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ij}=\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 which entails 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently the geodesic equation becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}x^{l}}{du^{2}}=0\implies x^{l}=a^{l}u+b^{l}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{l}$
\end_inset

 describes the direction and 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{l}$
\end_inset

 the location of a straight line.
 Now choose a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and a coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma'^{i}{}_{jk}=0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}x'^{l}}{du^{2}}=\mathcal{O}(u-u_{0})\implies x'^{l}=a'^{l}u+b'^{l}+\mathcal{O}((u-u_{0})^{3})
\]

\end_inset

after integration where note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\left(u-u_{0}\right)^{2})$
\end_inset

 like terms are absent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Tangent Vectors and Tangent Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and a geodesic passing through it.
 To arrive at the notion of tangent vectors we ask the following: How many
 parameters are needed to describe all possible geodesics that pass through
 this point? To answer this recall the geodesic equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}x^{l}}{du^{2}}+\Gamma^{l}{}_{ij}\frac{dx^{i}}{du}\frac{dx^{j}}{du}=0$
\end_inset

 and note that these constitute 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $l,i,j\in\{1,2,\dots n$
\end_inset

}) second order differential equations which means we must specify 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 constants.
 We already enforce 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{l}|_{u=u_{0}}=x_{0}^{l}$
\end_inset

 which is a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 conditions, that is, the geodesic must pass through the said point.
 Now we set the direction to completely specify the curve by requiring 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 more conditions: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.\frac{dx^{l}}{du}\right|_{\vec{x}=\vec{x}_{0}}=n^{l}
\]

\end_inset

where we define 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{l}$
\end_inset

 to be the 
\emph on
tangent vectors
\emph default
 to the geodesic at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we only need the direction to be specified by 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{l}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 can always be scaled.
 If we enforce 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{l}$
\end_inset

 exactly then the scaling (of the affine parameter) is also specified.
 We can now define the 
\emph on
tangent space
\emph default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 to be the space containing all vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{l}$
\end_inset

 through the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In this terminology, any vector in the tangent space specifies a geodesic
 through the given point.
 It is worth noting that two different 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

s might correspond to the same geodesic, e.g.
 the great circle on a sphere is one curve globally but locally will correspond
 to two tangent vectors (TODO: add figure).
 We close this section by relating tangent vectors for the same geodesic
 written in different coordinate systems.
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 coordinate system if it is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{l}=\left.dx^{l}/du\right|_{\vec{x}_{0}}$
\end_inset

 and in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 coordinate system it is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n'^{l}=\left.\frac{dx'^{l}}{du}\right|_{\vec{x}'_{0}}=\partial_{m}x'^{l}\left.\frac{dx^{m}}{du}\right|_{\vec{x}_{0}}=\partial_{m}x'^{l}n^{m},
\]

\end_inset

that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{l}$
\end_inset

 transforms as a tensor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Parallel Transport
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now in a position to ask what it would mean for two tangent vectors
 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{l}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{l}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

 to be parallel? Let us try the usual notion of parallel vectors from flat
 space where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}\parallel\vec{m}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{l}=\lambda m^{l}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Now if we look at their relation in a new coordinate system we would get
 
\begin_inset Formula $n'^{l}=\left.\partial_{k}x'^{l}\right|_{\vec{x}'_{1}}n^{k}$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $m'^{l}=\left.\partial_{k}x'^{l}\right|_{\vec{x}'_{2}}m^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Manifestly then two parallel tangent vectors may cease to be parallel in
 the new coordinate system the tangent vectors according to our naïve definition.
 This seems to suggest that there's no unambiguous way of determining if
 two tangents are parallel.
 We fix this demanding the said condition in a coordinate system which is
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to first order (where the first derivative of the metric disappears).
 Since we can make the space 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 only locally let us start by considering two close by points.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First choose a coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma'^{i}{}_{jk}(\vec{x}')=0$
\end_inset

 (or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial'_{i}g'_{jk}=0$
\end_inset

) and now consider two points 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x'}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x'}_{0}+\delta\vec{x}'_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We say that the tangents at these points, 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{l}$
\end_inset

, are parallel if 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{l}=\lambda m^{l}+\mathcal{O}(\delta x'^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 We also say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{m}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
parallel transport
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{m}'=\vec{n}'+\mathcal{O}(\delta x'^{2})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where we dropped the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 can be assumed to have the same normalisation
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Recall that in making 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma'^{i}{}_{jk}=0$
\end_inset

 we had only used the freedom in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

s (the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

s anyway didn't affect 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 as we saw) but we still had the freedom in specifying 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

s.
 These will define different coordinate systems each of which would have
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 zero.
 To ensure invariance under such coordinate transformations we had to add
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\delta x'^{2})$
\end_inset

 terms in our definition of parallel vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far our definition suffers from two issues.
 First, it is only defined for infinitesimally close points and second,
 it requires use to pick a specific coordinate system.
 We remedy this by determining the condition for parallel transport in an
 arbitrary frame and use the differential equation so obtained to parallel
 transport a given vector to finitely spaced points.
 Consider a curve between two points 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{(0)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{(1)}$
\end_inset

 parametrised by 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 which starts at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and ends at 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 We wish to start with a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{i}(0)$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{(0)}$
\end_inset

 and parallel transport it to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{(1)}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{i}(u)$
\end_inset

, implicitly defined, is known and we need to evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{i}(u+\delta u)$
\end_inset

.
 According to our definition of parallel transport we must first choose
 a coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial'_{i}g'_{jk}=0$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}'=\vec{x}'(u)$
\end_inset

 and then we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $n'^{i}(u+\delta u)=n'^{i}(u)+\mathcal{O}(\delta u^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Let us translate this condition back to the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 coordinate system.
 Recall 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{i}(u)=\left.\frac{\partial x^{i}}{\partial x'^{k}}\right|_{\vec{x}'(u)}n'^{k}(u)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
n^{i}(u+\delta u) & =\left.\frac{\partial x^{i}}{\partial x'^{k}}\right|_{\vec{x}'(u+\delta u)}n'^{k}(u+\delta u)\\
 & =\left.\frac{\partial x^{i}}{\partial x'^{k}}\right|_{\vec{x}'(u+\delta u)}\left(n'^{k}(u)+\mathcal{O}(\delta u^{2})\right) & \text{(using the transport equation)}\\
 & =\left(\left.\frac{\partial x^{i}}{\partial x'^{k}}\right|_{\vec{x}'(u)}+\frac{\partial^{2}x^{i}}{\partial x'^{l}\partial x'^{k}}\delta x'^{l}+\dots\right)\left(n'^{k}(u)+\mathcal{O}(\delta u^{2})\right)\\
 & =\left(\left.\frac{\partial x^{i}}{\partial x'^{k}}\right|_{\vec{x}'(u)}+\frac{\partial^{2}x^{i}}{\partial x'^{l}\partial x'^{k}}\frac{dx'^{l}}{du}\delta u+\dots\right)\left(n'^{k}(u)+\mathcal{O}(\delta u^{2})\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dn^{i}}{du}=\frac{\partial^{2}x^{i}}{\partial x'^{l}\partial x'^{k}}\frac{dx'^{l}}{du}n'^{k}=\frac{\partial^{2}x^{i}}{\partial x'^{l}\partial x'^{k}}\frac{\partial x'^{l}}{\partial x^{m}}\frac{\partial x'^{k}}{\partial x^{j}}\frac{dx^{m}}{du}n^{j}
\]

\end_inset

where in the last step we used the chain rule twice.
 This is better but it still depends on the primed coordinates.
 To remove this dependence recall the transformation of the Christofel symbol
 was given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Gamma'^{j}{}_{lk}=\frac{\partial x'^{j}}{\partial x^{\mu}}\frac{\partial x^{\nu}}{\partial x'^{l}}\frac{\partial x^{\rho}}{\partial x'^{k}}\Gamma^{\mu}{}_{\nu\rho}+\frac{\partial x'^{j}}{\partial x^{\mu}}\frac{\partial^{2}x^{\mu}}{\partial x'^{l}\partial x'^{k}}=0
\]

\end_inset

which upon multiplication with 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial x^{i}/\partial x'^{j}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cancel{\delta_{\mu}^{i}}\frac{\partial^{2}x^{\cancelto{i}{\mu}}}{\partial x'^{l}\partial x'^{k}}=-\cancel{\delta_{\mu}^{i}}\frac{\partial x^{\nu}}{\partial x'^{l}}\frac{\partial x^{\rho}}{\partial x'^{k}}\Gamma^{\cancelto{i}{\mu}}{}_{\nu\rho}.
\]

\end_inset

The term involving second derivatives is the one we would like to replace
 in our initial equation.
 This trading of second derivatives for a Christofel symbol and first derivative
s is useful because the first derivatives become delta functions upon multiplica
tion with tensor like transformation factors.
 Using this we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dn^{i}}{du} & =-\frac{\partial x^{\nu}}{\partial x'^{l}}\frac{\partial x^{\rho}}{\partial x'^{k}}\Gamma^{i}{}_{\nu\rho}\frac{\partial x'^{l}}{\partial x^{m}}\frac{\partial x'^{k}}{\partial x^{j}}\frac{dx^{m}}{du}n^{j}\\
 & =-\Gamma^{i}{}_{\nu\rho}\delta_{m}^{\nu}\delta_{j}^{\rho}\frac{dx^{m}}{du}n^{j}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which yields the final 
\emph on
parallel transport equation
\emph default
 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\frac{dn^{i}}{du}+\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}n^{j}\frac{dx^{k}}{du}=0}
\]

\end_inset

where we changed dummy indices and used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}=\Gamma^{i}{}_{kj}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that in our derivation we did not make any assumptions about the curve.
 In particular it needn't be a geodesic.
 We can also show that the equation is parametrisation independent as follows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u=f(v)$
\end_inset

 and note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dn^{i}}{du}=\frac{dv}{du}\frac{dn^{i}}{dv},\,\frac{dx^{k}}{du}=\frac{dv}{du}\frac{dx^{k}}{du}\implies\frac{dv}{du}\left[\frac{dn^{i}}{du}+\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}n^{j}\frac{dx^{k}}{du}\right]=0.
\]

\end_inset

This is unlike the geodesic equation which was derived for a specific parametris
ation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note also that this equation is coordinate invariant because the coordinate
 system 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 was chosen arbitrarily.
 This can also be seen explicitly by choosing another coordinate system
 
\begin_inset Formula $x''$
\end_inset

 and using 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{i}=n''^{k}\partial''_{k}x^{i}$
\end_inset

, the transformation of the Christofel symbol and 
\begin_inset Formula $dx^{i}/du=\partial''_{r}x^{i}dx''^{r}/du$
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial x^{i}}{\partial x''^{r}}\left(\frac{dn''^{r}}{du}+\Gamma''^{r}{}_{jk}n''^{j}\frac{dx''^{k}}{du}\right)=0
\]

\end_inset

which we leave as an exercise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can also be shown that the norm of a tangent vector is preserved under
 parallel transport, viz.
 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(g_{ij}n^{i}n^{j}\right)/du=0$
\end_inset

.
 One way to proceed is to evaluate this explicitly as 
\begin_inset Formula $dn^{i}/du$
\end_inset

 is known and use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $dg_{ij}/du=\partial_{k}g_{ij}dx^{k}/du$
\end_inset

.
 The neater method is to note that a scalar is invariant under coordinate
 transformations and therefore use a coordinate frame where the first derivative
 of the metric vanishes.
 Further the transport equation yields 
\begin_inset Formula $dn'/du=0$
\end_inset

 which completes the proof.
 This is not surprising because we derived all our results from the requirement
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $n'(u+\delta u)=n'(u)+\mathcal{O}(\delta u^{2})$
\end_inset

 where the norm is explicitly preserved to first order.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe that we started with choosing any vector from the tangent space
 at a given point and parallel transported it along an arbitrary curve to
 another point.
 Now instead consider the geodesic equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}x^{i}}{du^{2}}+\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}\frac{dx^{k}}{du}\frac{dx^{j}}{du}=0
\]

\end_inset

and use the definition for a tangent to the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{i}=dx^{i}/du$
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dn^{i}}{du}+\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}n^{j}\frac{dx^{k}}{du}=0
\]

\end_inset

which is the parallel transport equation! This means that the geodesic is
 a curve such that its tangent vectors are parallel transported from any
 given tangent on the curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Monodromy Matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we will try to understand what happens to a vector if it
 is parallel transported along a closed curve and how it might be an interesting
 object that captures curvature of the space.
 Imagine a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 starting at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{(1)}$
\end_inset

 and ending at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{(2)}$
\end_inset

.
 Also consider a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}_{(1)}$
\end_inset

 in the tangent space at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{(1)}$
\end_inset

 is transported to the end of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}_{(2)}$
\end_inset

.
 We can find a relation between these by integrating the parallel transport
 equation along the curve.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{(2)}^{i}=M^{i}{}_{j}n_{(1)}^{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
\begin_inset Formula $M^{i}{}_{j}$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}_{(1)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}_{(2)}$
\end_inset

 (where the symbols are as defined above).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proof sketch
\end_layout

\end_inset

To see this, recall that the parallel transport equation is linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For simplicity imagine that the tangent space is two dimensional (at both
 ends of the curve).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}_{(1)},\vec{n}'_{(1)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}_{(2)},\vec{n}'_{(2)}$
\end_inset

 span the space at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{(1)},\vec{x}_{(2)}$
\end_inset

 respectively and further assume 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{(2)}^{\prime i}=M^{i}{}_{j}n{}_{(1)}^{\prime j}$
\end_inset

.
 Any vector in the first tangent space can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{m}_{(1)}=\alpha\vec{n}_{(1)}+\beta\vec{n}_{(1)}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 which must transform under 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{i}{}_{j}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{i}{}_{j}m^{j}=\alpha M^{i}{}_{j}n_{(1)}^{j}+\beta M^{i}{}_{j}n_{(1)}^{\prime j}$
\end_inset

 by linearity of the transport equation.
 Finally we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{m}_{(2)}=\alpha\vec{n}{}_{(2)}+\beta\vec{n}'_{(2)}$
\end_inset

 which shows that once the transformation of the basis is known the transformati
on of every other vector is fixed and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{i}{}_{j}$
\end_inset

 can't depend on the vector itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dependence therefore would be restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{i}{}_{j}=M^{i}{}_{j}(\vec{x}_{(1)},\vec{x}_{(2)},c)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $-c$
\end_inset

 represents the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 starting from the other end, what can be said about 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{i}{}_{j}(\vec{x}_{(1)},\vec{x}_{(2)},-c)$
\end_inset

? First note the following.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
The parallel transport equation is reversible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proof sketch
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This follows from independence of parametrisation.
 Use 
\begin_inset Formula $v=1-u$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $u=1\leftrightarrow v=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u=0\leftrightarrow v=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $du\leftrightarrow-dv$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dn^{i}}{du}+\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}n^{j}\frac{dx^{k}}{du}=0\leftrightarrow\frac{dn^{i}}{dv}+\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}n^{j}\frac{dx^{k}}{dv}=0$
\end_inset

 so we essentially solve the same equation with the boundary conditions
 reversed.
 (Aside: Note that even for Newton's law this holds; in 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}x/dt^{2}=F(x)$
\end_inset

 send 
\begin_inset Formula $dt\to-dt$
\end_inset

 and you get the same equation but if the force term depended on 
\begin_inset Formula $dx/dt$
\end_inset

 (like friction for instance) then this doesn't work.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let the reversed solution be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(M(\vec{x}_{(1)},\vec{x}_{(2)},c)^{-1}\right)^{i}{}_{j}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{(1)}^{i}=\left(M(\vec{x}_{(1)},\vec{x}_{(2)},c)^{-1}\right)^{i}{}_{j}n_{(2)}^{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Also by definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{(1)}^{i}=M(\vec{x}_{(2)},\vec{x}_{(1)},-c)^{i}{}_{j}n_{(2)}^{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the two equations hold for arbitrary tangent vectors we conclude
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M(\vec{x}_{(2)},\vec{x}_{(1)},-c)=M^{-1}(\vec{x}_{(1)},\vec{x}_{(2)},c).
\]

\end_inset

If we had 
\begin_inset Formula $dn^{i}/du+\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}n'\left|dx^{j}/du\right|=0$
\end_inset

 then the equation would not be reversible and the aforesaid conclusion
 wrong.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider two curves 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset

 joining the points 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{(1)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{(2)}$
\end_inset

.
 In general 
\begin_inset Formula $M(\vec{x}_{(1)},\vec{x}_{(2)},c_{1})\neq M(\vec{x}_{(1)},\vec{x}_{(2)},c_{2})$
\end_inset

 but what happens if we consider the closed curve 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}-c_{2}$
\end_inset

? We can write this transformation as first going from 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 then returning from 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $-c_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We write this in the reversed order in the matrix (because it operates
 on objects on the right conventionally) as below.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
M(\vec{x}_{(1)},\vec{x}_{(1)},c_{1}-c_{2}) & =M(\vec{x}_{(2)},\vec{x}_{(1)},-c_{2})M(\vec{x}_{(1)},\vec{x}_{(2)},c_{1})\\
 & =M(\vec{x}_{(1)},\vec{x}_{(2)},c_{2})^{-1}M(\vec{x}_{(1)},\vec{x}_{(2)},c_{1})\\
 & \neq\mathbb{I}\,\text{(in general)}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{j}^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This object, the
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
matrix corresponding to the
\end_layout

\end_inset

 parallel transport operation of a vector around a closed loop 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $M(\vec{x},\vec{x},c)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\emph on
Monodromy matrix
\emph default
 around 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 It has an interesting coordinate invariant property.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
Consider coordinate systems 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $M'=\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{n}^{i}=M(\vec{x},\vec{x},c)^{i}{}_{j}n^{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Translate to another coordinate system to get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{n}'^{i} & =\frac{\partial x'^{i}}{\partial x^{p}}\tilde{n}^{p}\\
 & =\frac{\partial x^{\prime i}}{\partial x^{p}}M^{p}{}_{q}n^{q}\\
 & =\underbrace{\frac{\partial x^{\prime i}}{\partial x^{p}}M^{p}{}_{q}\frac{\partial x^{q}}{\partial x'^{j}}}_{M^{\prime i}{}_{j}}n^{\prime j}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where if 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{p}{}_{q}=\delta^{p}{}_{q}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $M'^{p}{}_{q}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{p}{}_{q}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that this proof would fail for 
\begin_inset Formula $M(\vec{x}_{1},\vec{x}_{2},c)$
\end_inset

 because the the two other factors in the bracketed expression would not
 become a kronecker delta as they would have been evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We now wish to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{ijkl}=0$
\end_inset

 entails that 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

 under some assumptions about connectedness of the underlying space.
 The reverse statement also holds as we shall see soon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
The Reimann Tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{ijkl}=0$
\end_inset

 entails that 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

 (if the space has no holes [TODO: make this precise]).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proof sketch for small curves to 
