 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dn^{i}}{du}=-\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}n^{j}(u)\frac{dx^{j}}{du}.
\]

\end_inset

The strategy would be to keep terms of order 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and then integrate to find 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The result would be correct to order 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\epsilon)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we use this 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{i}$
\end_inset

 and integrate to get 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{i}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\epsilon^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 We already know that 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{(0)}^{j}$
\end_inset

 is of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(1)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $dx^{i}/du=\mathcal{O}(1)$
\end_inset

.
 There's no reason to assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}$
\end_inset

 is small at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 so we simply integrate the following expression
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dn^{i}}{du}=-\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}(x_{(0)})n_{(0)}^{j}\frac{dx^{k}}{du}+\mathcal{O}(\epsilon)
\]

\end_inset

to get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n^{i}(u)=n_{(0)}^{i}-\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}(x_{0})n_{(0)}^{j}(x^{j}(u)-x_{(0)}^{j})+\mathcal{O}(\epsilon^{2})
\]

\end_inset

as recall 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{j}=\mathcal{O}(\epsilon)$
\end_inset

.
 Note also that we integrate to some arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 not to 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 We will now integrate the same expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $dn^{i}/du$
\end_inset

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{i}$
\end_inset

 correct to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(\epsilon^{3})$
\end_inset

 but set 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging in and retaining first order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dn^{i}}{du} & =-\left\{ \Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}(x_{(0)})+\partial_{l}\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}(x_{(0)})\underbrace{(x^{l}-x_{(0)}^{l})}_{\mathcal{O}(\epsilon)}\right\} \left\{ n_{(0)}^{i}-\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}(x_{0})n_{(0)}^{j}\underbrace{(x^{j}(u)-x_{(0)}^{j})}_{\mathcal{O}(\epsilon)}\right\} \frac{dx^{k}}{du}\\
 & =-\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}n_{(0)}^{j}\frac{dx^{k}}{du}-\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}\Gamma^{j}{}_{pq}n_{(0)}^{p}(x^{q}-x_{(0)}^{q})\frac{dx^{k}}{du}+\partial_{q}\Gamma^{i}{}_{pk}(x^{q}-x_{(0)}^{q})n_{(0)}^{p}\frac{dx^{k}}{du}+\mathcal{O}(\epsilon^{2})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we suppressed the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{(0)}$
\end_inset

 while writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 in the second line for brevity and changed dummy indices for aesthetics.
 The first term would integrate to zero as 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{k}$
\end_inset

 starts at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $u=0$
\end_inset

 and ends at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 We will replace 
\begin_inset Formula $dx^{k}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $d(x^{k}-x_{(0)}^{k})$
\end_inset

 and write the last term first to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
n^{i}(\epsilon) & =n_{(0)}^{i}+\left(\partial_{q}\Gamma^{i}{}_{pk}-\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}\Gamma^{j}{}_{pq}\right)n_{(0)}^{p}\oint_{0}^{\epsilon}(x^{q}-x_{(0)}^{q})\frac{d(x^{k}-x_{(0)}^{k})}{du}du+\mathcal{O}(\epsilon^{3}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that if the boundary term is zero we can shift the derivative with
 a minus sign, viz.
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x-x_{(0)}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\left(y^{q}dy^{k}+dy^{q}y^{k}\right)=\int d(y^{q}y^{k})=0\implies\int y^{q}dy^{k}=-\int y^{k}dy^{q}$
\end_inset

.
 This means the integral is anti-symmetric in the indices 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the symmetric part of the multiplying tensor will not contribute to
 the final expression.
 We therefore keep only the anti-symmetric part (in 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

) of it to obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
n^{i}(\epsilon) & =n_{(0)}^{i}+\frac{1}{2}\left[\partial_{q}\Gamma^{i}{}_{pk}-\partial_{k}\Gamma^{i}{}_{pq}-\Gamma^{i}{}_{jk}\Gamma^{j}{}_{pq}+\Gamma^{i}{}_{jq}\Gamma^{j}{}_{pk}\right]n_{(0)}^{p}\oint_{0}^{\epsilon}(x^{q}-x_{(0)}^{q})\frac{d(x^{k}-x_{(0)}^{k})}{du}\\
 & =n_{(0)}^{i}+\frac{1}{2}\left.R^{i}{}_{pkq}\right|_{\vec{x}_{(0)}}\oint(x^{q}-x_{(0)}^{q})\frac{d(x^{k}-x_{(0)}^{k})}{du}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

See what we did there? We got the Reimann Tensor into the equation.
 Now since 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{i}{}_{pqk}|_{\vec{x}_{(0)}}=0$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n^{i}(\epsilon)=n_{(0)}^{i}+\mathcal{O}(\epsilon^{3})
\]

\end_inset

which means 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{i}{}_{j}(\vec{x}_{0},\vec{x}_{0},c)=\delta^{i}{}_{j}+\mathcal{O}(\epsilon^{3})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That was already quite satisfying but of course valid only for small loops
 and still not exact.
 We will actually use that as a lemma in the full proof.
 To be able to proceed we will need another small result.
 With reference to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:How-are-the"

\end_inset

 we want to know how the monodromy matrix evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

 around a loop and that evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

 around the same loop are related.
 Note that because the parallel transport was an integral we can break it
 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M(\vec{x}_{1},\vec{x}_{1},c_{1}+c_{2})=M(x_{2},x_{1},c_{2})M(x_{1},x_{2},c_{1})
\]

\end_inset

 where we need to use the reversed order as it is an operator.
 Note that using 
\begin_inset Formula $M(x_{2},x_{2},c_{2}+c_{1})=M(x_{1},x_{2},c_{1})M(x_{2},x_{1},c_{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M(x_{2},x_{1},c_{2})^{-1}=M(x_{1},x_{2},-c_{2})$
\end_inset

 we can write the second term of the aforesaid equation as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M(\vec{x}_{1},\vec{x}_{1},c_{1}+c_{2})=M(x_{2},x_{1},c_{2})M(x_{2},x_{2},c_{2}+c_{1})M(x_{1},x_{2},-c_{2})
\]

\end_inset

which means that monodromy matrices evaluated at two different points in
