\begin_layout Claim
Consider two points 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider two distinct paths, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2}$
\end_inset

 that continues from 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and goes back to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The monodromy evaluated around this loop starting from 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are related as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M(x_{1},x_{1},c_{1}+c_{2})=M(x_{2},x_{1},c_{2})M(x_{2},x_{2},c_{2}+c_{1})M^{-1}(x_{2},x_{1},c_{2})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M(x_{i},x_{f},c)$
\end_inset

 is the parallel transport transformation matrix for a vector from 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{i}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{f}$
\end_inset

 along the path 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular if 
\begin_inset Formula $M(x_{2},x_{2},c_{2}+c_{1})=\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

 then so is 
\begin_inset Formula $M(x_{1},x_{1},c_{1}+c_{2})$
\end_inset

, viz.
 if the monodrome is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

 then the point from which you start doesn't matter.
 We can generalise a little.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A=SBS^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and we know 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\mathbb{I}+\mathcal{O}(\epsilon)$
\end_inset

 then we also know 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathbb{I}+S\mathcal{O}(\epsilon)S^{-1}=\mathbb{I}+\mathcal{O}(\epsilon)$
\end_inset

, viz.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is close to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

 then so is 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

